e Marshall, Grace Paley, and others, Goffman unfolds a story of two peoples with powerful biblical and mythic connections that replay themselves in contemporary circumstances. In doing so, he uncovers layers of meaning in works that dramatize this turbulent, paradoxical relationship, and reveals how this relationship is paradigmatic of multicultural American self-invention.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAfrican Americans in literature. 0aAfrican AmericansxRelations with Jews. 0aAmerican literaturexAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturexJewish authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aBlack people in literature. 0aBlack peoplexRelations with Jews. 0aEthnic relations in literature. 0aJews in literature. 0aJewszUnited StatesxIntellectual life. 0aJudaism and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aLiterature and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRace relations in literature. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791492079423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791492079/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles